gimens of simplified living and transcendental mysticism, Smith shows how disciplines of attention became the spiritual exercises of a distracted age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDisciplinexIn literature. 0aDistraction (Psychology)xIn literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aAnimal magnetism.  aAsceticism.  aAttention economy.  aAuthor.  aBernard Stiegler.  aBiography.  aByzantine Empire.  aCamp meeting.  aCapital punishment.  aCareer.  aCatechism.  aChristianity.  aChurch architecture.  aClassroom.  aColored.  aConversion narrative.  aCriticism.  aDefinition of religion.  aDistraction.  aDivine judgment.  aEthics.  aEvangelicalism.  aHannah Arendt.  aHannah More.  aHarvard University Press.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aHypocrisy.  aIdentity politics.  aIrritability.  aLaborer.  aLearning.  aLeaves of Grass.  aLiterary genre.  aLiterature.  aLydia Maria Child.  aMeditations.  aModernity.  aNat Turner.  aOf Education.  aOppression.  aOxford University Press.  aPamphlet.  aPhilosopher.  aPiety.  aPoetry.  aPolitical culture.  aProse.  aProtestantism.  aReformatory.  aReligion.  aSanctification.  aSelf-Reliance.  aSelf-interest.  aSimone Weil.  aSlave rebellion.  aSlavery.  aSong of Myself.  aSpiritual Exercises of Ignatius of Loyola.  aSpiritual autobiography.  aSpirituality.  aStanford University Press.  aSympathy.  aThought.  aTranscendentalism.  aUniversity of Chicago Press.  aWalter Benjamin.  aWickedness.  aWriting.  aYale University Press.1 aApess, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaird, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l